On Sunday 27th June 2021, I'll be challenging myself to run the Brighton Half Marathon (eek!) in aid of a very worthy cause, Macmillan Cancer Support. 

In the UK, 1 in 2 people will be diagnosed with cancer in their lifetime. Macmillan Cancer Support work tirelessly to provide physical, emotional and financial support to help those with cancer live life as fully as they can. 

It hasn't been an easy year, but whatever you are able to donate will be greatly appreciated! Every penny counts and goes towards vital care for those with cancer. Thank you!

Currently seeking open minded individuals to join me spiritually or via social media. The more the merrier! Week commencing 04/01/2021 will be a preparation week full of healthy eating, meditation & everyday small stamina building excersises.

Join me! You can run it, walk it or do it in fancy dress.

story:
Who can forget the telepathic little and large partnerships of John Toshack and Kevin Keegan, Tore Andre Flo and Gianfranco Zola, Jermain Defoe and Peter Crouch...

It is a factor that may have died out in the modern day but in 2021 Big Joe Matthews and Little Joe Mills are rolling back the years with a classic big man and little man partnership for a good cause.

We will be running 2,021km in the year 2021 between us, approximately 40km per week or 168km per month. If you know us, you will appreciate that we are not seasoned athletes and this will be no easy task.

The money raised will be going to a charity that means a lot to both of us due to family losses in recent years, MacMillan Cancer Support. 

Feel free to follow our progress via the instagram link below and thanks in advance for any donations you make!

https://instagram.com/2021joesrun

story:
August 2020 i was diagnosed with stage 1b melanoma. 2 operations and it was all cut away but I am under the care of the SCN nurse and consultant for the next 5 years. I want to give something back to macmillian because the help and support I received really helped me along the way. Hearing the word Cancer hit me like a ton of bricks and I thought right thats it for me, I have kids I'm only 35 at the time. I went through all emotions impossible to the point I hated the world constantly asking why me. But with the help support love from my family and friends, and the amazing help and support from macmillian I got through it. 

So many people are affected by cancer and for me personally I was very fortunate they had caught it in the early stages. Mines started from a mole on my back which changed over 9 months, I check my body once a month as recommended, my advice is something doesn't look right or you worry get it checked dont put it off until 2moro when u can act today.

Not only do I want to raise a small amount towards a fantastic cause I want to raise awareness. I want people to still receive the support I had and continue to have from macmillian and they rely on fundraising so its time for me to give something back.

story:
Cancer has and will continue to touch all of our lives in one way or another.
Personally it has impacted on my life by taking my Nan, but Uncle was lucky enough to beat Cancer - loosing his Kidney in the process. 

When you find out a young and fit friend has silently been diagnosed with cancer, it kind of hits you different. Starting his treatment quietly and without fuss, I wanted to do something to raise money in dedication. There is little we can do support one another during these times from the other shitty C; words only go so far and I wanted to do something physically to show my own support. 
 He said Macmillan has provided him with great support, and thus I will be doing this challenge. 

I haven't ran in several months since it's been dark of an evening, so wish me luck....

story:
Some of you may know that my incredible grandad suddenly and sadly passed away on 2nd November 2020, aged 86.

The British Heart Foundation was a charity that helped my grandad, Peter, throughout his later years. It was my grandad's wish for any donations to be made to the British Heart Foundation,  in his loving memory. 

I thought it was the least I could do, to help raise these funds. Therefore, I am running 100km throughout January (cold I know!). Please donate as little or as much as you would like, any donation will be greatly appreciated and will definitely provide motivation to keep running!! Any free massages will also be welcomed (haha)....

Thank you all so much in advance, my grandad and family would hugely appreciate this too! 

RIP Peter Batchelor, a loving Dad, Brother and Grandad.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
If you knew my Gran you know she was a very caring, charitable woman. So, it only seems right that in memory of her; I do my bit to raise money and awareness for a charity that supports something that affected her health massively throughout her life. 

She had the biggest heart to give but unfortunately not a very healthy one. 

Sadly, on Christmas Day she passed away from a heart attack, aged 66. 

I know people wont have a lot to give just after the Christmas period but I know a little goes a long way. Even just your awareness means a lot to us all. 


Below, I have some facts and figures  from the BHF site-

  • Heart and circulatory diseases cause more than a quarter of all deaths in the UK, that’s nearly 170,000 deaths each year – an average of 460 deaths each day or one every three minutes in the UK.
  • There are around 7.4 million people living with heart and circulatory disease in the UK: 3.9 million men and 3.5 million women.
  • Coronary heart disease (CHD) is the most common type of heart and circulatory disease. It is also the most common cause of heart attack and the single biggest killer worldwide.
  • In the UK there are more than 100,000 hospital admissions each year due to heart attacks: that's one every five minutes.
  • Around 1.4 million people alive in the UK today have survived a heart attack.
  • Over 900,000 people in the UK are living with heart failure.
  • Strokes cause around 36,000 deaths in the UK each year and are the biggest cause of severe disability.
  • People with a family history of coronary heart disease are much more likely to develop vascular dementia.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page, it really means a lot.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
This January, I will be going Meatless as part of my workplace’s ‘Healthy Habit Month’ for the British Heart Foundation to encourage healthy eating habits for the new year. This will be the second time I will be going meatless, after achieving 4 months vegetarian from January last year. I hope to succeed further with the healthy habit this year as it is better for your heart and for the environment.

4 years ago, I lost a very important and special person in my life. My grandad Bri was the kindest man you could ever meet, and sadly passed away on 28th December 2016 of a very sudden and unexpected heart attack. Grandad Bri worked for Greenway Environmental for many years and was a special member of the company, and it if for this reason we decided to become charity partners with the British Heart Foundation. The GRG Waste UK family will be raising money throughout the year in memory of my Grandad Bri and other family members of the group lost to heart related diseases. 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Rod Ashman was man with a big heart. He gave time to so many over his 83 years. Rod sadly passed away peacefully on 22nd December 2020 at Wythenshawe hospital after a short illness.

After a heart attack in 2011 Rod had surgery, at Wythenshawe Hospital, to repair the damage. He also had a pacemaker and defibrillator fixed which, I have no doubt, extended his life considerably.  He was always grateful of both the treatment available to him at that time, and the way in which it was provided. 

In order to assist the charity to continue it's amazing work in research and development, and assist in prolonging the lives of so many, we, Rod`s family ask that you consider a small donation to this worthy charity in his memory.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
Some 3 years ago I was diagnosed with multiple slipped disc and told by a consultant I never run a mile again. At that time I was quite a bit overweight and worried about my future health, especially risks such as heart attacks and diabetes.  I did not want to be defeated staying unhealthy and therefore set myself the challenge to loose weight and  strengthen my body -needless to say 6 Stone lighter and 450 miles done in 2020 I can happily say I have defeated the odds.

Therefore this year to top it all off I would like to run the London Landmarks Half Marathon  to raise money for the British Heart Foundation who has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives.

Any donations no matter how small are much appreciated thank you everyone in advance for supporting me.

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Thank you for taking the time to read my story.

When I was 19 years old I was diagnosed with juvenile macular degeneration and over the last 22 years have slowly lost my central vision.

5 years ago I was fortunate enough to be matched with an amazing guide dog who helps me so much everyday and helped me gain my confidence back. 

Without this fabulous charity many people with sight loss are restricted to their own homes, the difference these amazing animals make is beyond imaginable!!

The sponsorship money you donate will truly make a difference. £140 could buy a Starter Kit for a new guide dog owner, containing everything they need to start a life with their new guide dog, this includes the iconic white harness. Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services, like our guide dogs, to people with sight loss. So, a huge thank you!

story: Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 618 children and young people from across the UK arrive. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support to give seriously ill children the best chance to fulfil their potential. A better future for seriously ill children STARTS HERE.

story:
On January 3rd 2021 Edward Poulter sadly lost his life. We lost our legend. 

Edward, Eddie as most of you know him. A husband of 46 years to his most treasured soul mate Eileen, dad to two sons and the most tremendous Grandad, not forgetting an incredible Great-Grandad. 

A golfing extraordinaire, a fabulous cook (nan over saw some of that) and a true gentleman. He was funny, gentle, kind and so loving. Each and every person that met him, would remember him forever. 

Everyone that ever met my grandad would always remember him for being one of the nicest people you'd ever met. 

As for being a grandad, I always used to describe him as your typical grandad, typical in that he was the one who cuddled you the tightest, the one who always spoilt you, fed you up until you burst, always asked how you were and took interest in your life and who cheeklily put money in your hand when he left you. He was the sweetest, kindest grandad who completely made my childhood full of the most special times and fondest memories. I challenge you to find a better husband, dad, grandad, great-grandad, son, brother and friend....you won't. One in a million weren't you! 

He had so many friends who I know just loved being around him, he'd always talk about his friends and family to everyone. He truly was the proudest man of everyone he had in his life. 

I think I speak for everyone when I say we are utterly devastated. 

My nan had the idea of setting up a donation page for Great Ormond Street, he probably spoke about it lots to some, but for those who don't know it was a charity close to home. 

Myself and his two great-grandchildren have been cared for by this wonderful hospital for many years and the two little one's continue to be treated and cared for by them for life long illnesses. 

Instead of flowers my nan would like you to make a small donation to this charity, we have been informed funeral flowers are sadly just thrown away so feel its a better cause for money to go to charity. 

Once this current situation is over we will throw him the party/send off he deserves. He loved a Bbq and drink up didn't he and that is what we will give him. 

Thank you all for your continued support, kind messages and for being there. 

xxx

Love you Ed/Dad/Grandad 

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

I’d like to thank you in advance for any support and donations to such a fantastic and life changing charity. I will keep you updated throughout the 50 days. 

Thank you and stay safe xxx

eventName: GOSH London to Paris with Discover Adventure 2021
story:
Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, over 600 children and young people from across the UK arrive for life-changing treatments. 

I'm so proud to be riding in GOSH's 2021  London to Paris Charity Cycle ride as part of the team called "Are We There Yet?".   Over 4 days from July 14th, we will cover 300 miles / 482 Km.  It's going to be a lot of work facing some new challenges that I have never done before. I am not a cyclist or at least not yet... 

I wanted to take on something new and positive and to give something back to our Health Services. Especially in this difficult time of Covid and the extra pressure it puts on our Health Services and the patients they support. 

Great Ormond Street Hospital OSH provide wonderful brilliant support to Children when they most need care, expertise and love. 

Everyday they perform miracles. The Children they care for are so positive and full of courage even when they often face the biggest challenges in their lives. 

This extract from the  GOSH website I think says it all very well. 

"Every day, young lives hang in the balance as patients, families and staff battle the most complex illnesses. Every day, the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs that change the lives of thousands of children – and change the world.

Despite the greatest challenges a child can face, the hospital is a place where being sick does not always mean being sad. And it’s a place where you’ll find – today and every day – some of the bravest people you could ever meet."   Read more at https://www.gosh.org/what-we-do.

This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support. Please help me to support GOSH and the Children they care for now and for the future. 

Thank you.

Chris.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

My name is Pat Paine and after a 4 year battle with cancer, I found that you can live happily with it, with all the care I got from family, friends and the medical profession.

The trick is to keep positive, keep smiling and "just get on with it"

Life did get tough and it got me in the end but if you are affected by Cancer, get help quickly, it may save your life.

Keep smiling.

Lot's of love.

Pat  xx

We are the world’s largest charity dedicated to saving lives through research.

charity.name: Cancer Research UK
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 1089464, Scotland SC041666
story:
This year I will be running 2 miles a day throughout during February to raise money for cancer research. 

Covid-19 has put a huge strain on cancer services in the UK. This strain has been felt in all areas, including screening, diagnosis and treatment. Figures have revealed the sheer scale of this disruption – estimating that over 2 million people in the UK are waiting for screening, tests and treatment since the first lockdown began. Patients shouldn’t have to wait for Covid-19 to be over before getting the treatment they need. 

There has been a significant drop in the number of urgent referrals for cancer, with 290,000 less people being referred for further tests than normal. This drop is largely because fewer people are going to the GP with symptoms that might be cancer, GPs are reluctant to risk sending their patient to hospital for further tests, and some diagnostic services – such as endoscopies – have been put on hold due to the risk of spreading Covid-19. 

Despite national guidelines stating that urgent and essential cancer treatments must continue, the impact of Covid-19 has been felt in cancer wards across the country, with surgery hit the worst. Around 12,750 people are waiting for cancer surgery across the UK, as the number of operations has fallen to around 60% of expected levels. Chemotherapy has also taken a hit, with over 6,000 fewer people than expected receiving chemotherapy since lockdown began.

The Coronavirus pandemic has put a lot of lab-based research on hold and forced most researchers to change the way they work. With most university and hospital sites closed, laboratories have slowed down their activities and experiments have stopped. Researchers are continuing to work from home, writing papers, analysing data but the progress of research will slow down, and this will inevitably have an impact on researcher’s careers and the lives of people affected by cancer.

story:
My name is Sarah, I am 29 years old and am married to my childhood sweetheart and we have a gorgeous healthy 2 year old son. 

At age 20 I was diagnosed with stage 3 Colon cancer. As you can imagine it was terrifying even if I did tried to pretend like I wasn't scared. I tried to stay calm but to see my whole family and support network distraught I could pretend any longer. I was petrified I was going to die. 

The surgeons, the doctors, the nurses and every single person that was helping me were out of this world. Nothing was too much trouble, no diagram to explain everything was too much to ask and the friendliness and care I recieved was incredible. I was a very young patient for them all to be trea

ting for bowel cancer, which was new for them all, but they carried me through every step in a way I could comprehend (not enjoy but understand). The meetings and discussions that were carried out through many doctors nurses and professionals across the UK, to ensure I was given the best and fastest treatment was amazing. The course and plan of action was altered many times but only to ensure the best possible outcome for a young fertile, 20 year old girl. 

The final plan was surgery as soon as possible, to prevent the tumour from spreading into more lymph nodes as it was growing at a rapid rate. By July I was in surgery, 2 weeks after I started fertility treatment and 11 eggs were harvested from me and put into storage, in September I started the gruelling course of chemotherapy. 8 sessions every 3 weeks, each session lasting 8 hours+. I still remember the sickening feeling as it started to run through my veins. I dreaded the 3 week mark returning but I knew I had to stick with it. Finally the last session came around in February and in March 2013 I was put into remission. 

Without cancer research none of this would of been possible, the groundbreaking research is lifesaving and I am so thankful every day for the life I have been given. The battle was short in the grand scheme of being able to live a fulfilling life now.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Before Brian Forster passed away on 16th December, 2020, after contracting Covid-19, he had already expressed his wish to support Cancer Research UK -  a cause close to his heart having seen the impact the disease had on his daughter.

Brian was a wonderful, kind, loving husband, Dad and Grandad who is greatly missed. He dedicated 22 years of his life to the Royal Air Force, travelling around the world, and then pursued a career as an engineer in 'civvy street'. He had an incredible work ethic, bringing up a rather large family but was always looking for an opportunity to celebrate special events, bringing his family and friends together. He loved life. He will forever be in our hearts. 

Thank you for your donation to Cancer Research UK. Please take care of yourself and your family in this pandemic-ridden world.

story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit the JustGiving page set up for donations to be made to Marie Curie Cancer Care in memory of Donald Bates, who passed away peacefully, having suffered with cancer, on 11th December 2020.

Don received excellent support and palliative care from all the staff of the Marie Curie hospice, Solihull, meaning his final days were peaceful and comfortable.

Marie Curie nurses provide respectful and dignified care to those at the end of their life, as well as supporting families in the darkest moments but cannot do so without kind donations from the public.

For those who's lives were touched by Don, and for those who wish to support the wonderful work Marie Curie does, please give generously, that others may be similarly supported.

My family and I have set up this page in memory of my mum, Sue Gough, who has sadly passed away after a long illness, only aged 69. The Marie curie nurses provided great support to her and my family in the last few weeks of her life so we think this is a great way to show all our appreciation. 

She was much loved by all who knew her but due to the current Covid restrictions many will be unable to join us at her funeral. 

We hope this page will give them a chance to show their love and respect.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
2020 – What a strange year!

Pandemics and lockdowns and furlough… Suddenly we all found ourselves with more time on our hands than we knew what to do with! During my time being furloughed, I decided that I needed some form of exercise. Well, I wasn’t going to take up running at my tender old age, so my quest was simple; find a bike.

Eventually, through some miracle, I found one and I managed to get out and about. There I was, racking up the miles, getting fitter and falling into a pattern of regular exercise when I saw an advertisement to raise funds for a cancer charity – a story many of us can relate to. So, I got cracking, found some sponsorships, and completed the challenge with over £700 to donate. A great success!

Not being one to sit back and stop there, I turned my thoughts to something more personal.

Back in 2014, my life changed in a split second. January 22nd, 2014; the day my son Mike was taken from us off the coast of Cornwall. At 23 years old, Mike was a passionate fisherman, and that day he was out with his best mate looking for a fishing spot to settle down for the day. The last any of us heard from him, was his most recent Facebook status.

“Sex, drugs and rock and roll? Nah, fishing is the life for me!”

Then suddenly, a freak wave hit them both. His mate managed to hold on and call the emergency services, but Mike was swept out in seconds. The RNLI and air support were on the scene within 15 minutes. They never found him, and my life changed that day, forever.

But back to 2020; I had a lightbulb moment. I wanted to raise awareness again, and help the RNLI.

My challenge is to ride from the Weston super Mare RNLI station to Padstow RNLI station, visiting every other station on the way to thank the crews for what they do. The challenge will involve riding 200 miles over tough terrain with a total elevation of 16,000ft and will take four days to complete. I’m looking for a team of six to join me, with four of us already committed so far.

We are hoping to do the ride at the earliest possible date in spring inline with the latest Covid-19 restrictions - as soon as we have a confirmed date this will be posted - if you would like to show your support by joining us on a section of the ride then please e-mail me at philipmfbindon@hotmail.co.uk 

Come and join us, and ‘Ride your Bike for Mike’!
title: RNLI Weston-Super-Mare to Padstow Cycle Challenge

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

My name is Jack and I am 8 years old and me and my family will be taking part in The Big Winter Wander. We will not only be taking part for just one day but throughout January. We will be taking note and recording the animals we spot and find on our walks and we will do everything we can in the garden to encourage lots more wildlife visitors too. Our target is to raise £100 that will go directly to WWF to support and protect our wildlife. All donations, no matter how small will be very gratefully received and all money raised will be matched by the government. Please help us to protect our wildlife. Thank you, Jack

story:
Cotswold Way Challenge 2021 - Fight for Your World WWF

So I'm doing one of those things that seems to be popular for birthdays... especially since it's bloody lockdown and I can't do anything fun anyway!

So instead I'm going to train and do a massive walk (100km) through the Cotswold hills at the end of June. 

Would hugely appreciate the help from you lot to raise some cash for the WWF. I've been a WWF supporter for many years and I want to help out even more. We could all do a bit more to help our planet and the animals that live here, and it's sometimes hard to know where to start, so start here!

Spare some dough and join me in the  WWF Fight for your World!

Also, if anyone is keeyn to join me on this trek, feel free to join my team Chafing the Dream.  If you sign up before the end of January, you can register for £1. 

You can sign up here;

https://endurancecui.active.com/new/events/70347551/select-race?fbclid=IwAR3t3GjfnvmqM_pRBdTyix9-Da9rbOvcZB-C1JdpXgXKtJBRJxJtgWsI7Nk&rf=8ea157e16f5e47b3894b31659641c181&_p=14074830505109115

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: A child dies every two minutes from malaria. We are one of the world’s leading non profit organisations specialising in protecting the most vulnerable from the burden of malaria and other communicable diseases. To know more about how we spend your money and where we work, please visit our website.
charity.name: Malaria Consortium
story:
Over the past year the world has shut down to fight Covid-19 and in the UK we are facing another month of lockdown. We thought we would try use our time productively and raise money to help fight a disease that kills hundreds of thousands, mostly children in sub Saharan Africa, every year. 

What is so tragic about this is malaria is a preventable and treatable illness and it is estimated that nets can avert around 50 percent of malaria cases and reduce all-cause child mortality by approximately 18 percent.

We will be walking 250 miles from the 5th of Jan to the 31st.

So gis a few quid and help the kids.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
We're walking from St Albans (UK) to Cox's Bazaar (Bangladesh), 11,265km (7,000m), visiting Oxfam projects along the way. 

We'll see the challenges communities face from conflict, to Covid-19 to the impact of the climate emergency and how Oxfam is responding to support communities to thrive, not just survive. 

With your support, Oxfam can continue its life-saving work, it can continue to put together packages of food, give farming support, set up foodbanks, support education for women and girls, and provide cash to buy essentials.


For each £15 we raise, were helping more women to understand their rights, challenge discrimination and to take up leadership roles within their local communities.

For each £35, we will ensure families have access to emergency food supplies. 


£45 will provide one of our new handwashing stations to enable frequent handwashing and disease prevention.

With your support, communities can come together to help each other.

charity.name: Oxfam
story:
6km is the average distance walked in Sub-Saharan Africa to collect 1 person's  daily water supply of 15L

Its the least I can do...

Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. Together, we won't live with poverty.

charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped. Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus.

In addition to doing the yoga I will also become pescatarian and stop all unessential online shopping, to reduce my impact on the earth.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. Thank you.

charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
I am 8 years old I am planning to walk the 6 highest mountains in England during 2021. The mountains that I am going to walk up are:

Scafell Pike, Scafell, Helvellyn, Ill Crag, Broad Crag and Skiddaw.

The reason why I am raising money is because in High Hesket School I learnt about children living in poverty and not having enough to eat. We learnt about Marcus Rashford and his appeal to stop children living in hunger. I wanted to help raise money to stop children living in poverty and danger in this country and around the world.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story: Throughout the globe Covid-19 has spread rapidly. Although UK has seen its own share of illness and death we are very lucky enough to have first class healthcare service and government support in this crisis. Unfortunately others around the world are not so lucky. In an attempt to give back to those in need this February Isaac Guppy, Cam Graetz, Max Waldron and Julian Hannah have set themselves a challenge to run 300km each throughout the month (averaging 10km a day) in order to raise money for UNICEF. UNICEF, also known as the united nations children’s fund, is a United Nations agency responsible for providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. We extend the invitation to anyone who would like to join us on our ‘Rona Run’ or set your own challenge for the month and help support those in need!

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. 

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.
